 Yeah, he was a pretty amazing person.

00:01:56.600 --> 00:02:04.800
 And well, back to the subject of progesterone, which we left off last week talking about

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:09.880
 the Wall Street Journal article about this doctor who had done a lot of research on the

00:02:09.880 --> 00:02:17.720
 effect of progesterone on brain damage, both through accidents and through strokes, and

00:02:17.720 --> 00:02:20.080
 found it a very effective therapy.

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:25.080
 I think people recovered twice as fast and probably a lot of people recovered that wouldn't

00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:26.240
 have.

00:02:26.240 --> 00:02:28.560
 And there were no negative side effects.

00:02:28.560 --> 00:02:34.120
 And I asked you last week about any negative side effects you knew about progesterone.

00:02:34.120 --> 00:02:40.200
 And one thing you mentioned was the danger of being over anesthetized by it.

00:02:40.200 --> 00:02:45.720
 And I was just wondering, is that a danger from actually stopping your heart if you potentially

00:02:45.720 --> 00:02:46.720
 took too much?

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:51.560
 Or is that just from you might get into an accident if you fell asleep?

00:02:51.560 --> 00:02:55.880
 I think what it would do first is stop breathing.

00:02:55.880 --> 00:03:00.080
 But up to a certain point, it stimulates breathing.

00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:09.720
 So it's probably somewhat of an antidote to things like morphine, because progesterone,

00:03:09.720 --> 00:03:20.960
 as long as it's within something like several hundred milligrams at a time or per day, it's

00:03:20.960 --> 00:03:26.880
 like an imitation of pregnancy where it stimulates breathing.

00:03:26.880 --> 00:03:35.160
 But up in the pharmacological range of something like three or four thousand milligrams all

00:03:35.160 --> 00:03:43.160
 at once, then instead of being a stimulant to respiration, it just puts everything to

00:03:43.160 --> 00:03:45.720
 sleep.

00:03:45.720 --> 00:03:52.840
 And I think that would include the respiratory system at some very high level.

00:03:52.840 --> 00:04:02.960
 In Mexico, some students were experimenting with the idea that maybe progesterone works

00:04:02.960 --> 00:04:08.160
 like morphine because of those sedative effects.

00:04:08.160 --> 00:04:19.600
 And so they combined naloxone, the anti-morphine drug, with progesterone and their experimental

00:04:19.600 --> 00:04:20.600
 rat died.

00:04:20.600 --> 00:04:33.040
 And it was okay on a given amount of either of them, but that pretty much said that progesterone

00:04:33.040 --> 00:04:47.280
 isn't acting like morphine because the anti-morphine chemical seemed to exaggerate the anesthetic

00:04:47.280 --> 00:04:50.000
 effect of progesterone.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:56.440
 Is it the equivalent of saying that maybe water supports life, but if you drink too

00:04:56.440 --> 00:05:01.240
 much of it or fall into it, it can potentially kill you?

00:05:01.240 --> 00:05:08.540
 What's the range of the dose we're talking about for overdosing on progesterone?

00:05:08.540 --> 00:05:11.440
 No one really has done that.

00:05:11.440 --> 00:05:18.440
 My student's rat was the only death that I know of, even experimentally.

00:05:18.440 --> 00:05:30.360
 In the 1940s, Hans Elie had told his technicians to experiment with very big doses of progesterone.

00:05:30.360 --> 00:05:38.480
 And after doing some experiments, they said those high doses had killed the rats.

00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:40.200
 And he didn't believe it.

00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:43.360
 He said, "What did you do with them?"

00:05:43.360 --> 00:05:47.200
 And they went to the garbage and fished them out.

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:54.960
 And he published photographs holding them by the skin on their back.

00:05:54.960 --> 00:06:02.320
 They looked sort of like a wet dishrag, just the most relaxed rat you ever saw.

00:06:02.320 --> 00:06:07.720
 But they weren't dead, they were just deeply sleepy.

00:06:07.720 --> 00:06:10.560
 But his technicians had thought they'd died.

00:06:10.560 --> 00:06:21.640
 So I'm not even sure that my students were not mistaken about the naloxone and progesterone

00:06:21.640 --> 00:06:24.880
 combination, but they thought the rat had died.

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:25.880
 I see.

00:06:25.880 --> 00:06:29.040
 Well, I think that settles that then.

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:35.280
 So it's only potentially fatal in enormous quantities.

00:06:35.280 --> 00:06:36.760
 Yeah.

00:06:36.760 --> 00:06:46.520
 And you also said that vasectomies in men tended to lower progesterone in those men.

00:06:46.520 --> 00:06:49.440
 And I was wondering, what's the mechanism behind that?

00:06:49.440 --> 00:06:59.280
 Well, it wasn't consistent, but when the men had very distinct symptoms following the vasectomies,

00:06:59.280 --> 00:07:06.560
 they studied what was going on and found that the ones who had the symptoms had very low

00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:10.320
 to almost zero progesterone.

00:07:10.320 --> 00:07:15.080
 And they recovered when they gave them progesterone.

00:07:15.080 --> 00:07:20.480
 But most of the men having vasectomies didn't have any symptoms.

00:07:20.480 --> 00:07:35.120
 And so my interpretation is that it's a biological analog to what's reasonable in the female.

00:07:35.120 --> 00:07:44.200
 If the female has an infection in the uterus or tubes, for example, it's biologically

00:07:44.200 --> 00:07:51.840
 reasonable to turn off progesterone production so that pregnancy can't happen.

00:07:51.840 --> 00:08:00.520
 And so irritation in the uterus or tube in the female causes sterility by turning off

00:08:00.520 --> 00:08:03.600
 progesterone and increasing estrogen.

00:08:03.600 --> 00:08:11.960
 And I think the event in the men who had the bad reaction to vasectomy, I think it was

00:08:11.960 --> 00:08:24.160
 the biological equivalent of a signal traveling up the ducts to the testicle, maybe to the

00:08:24.160 --> 00:08:29.520
 pituitary, turning off steroid production.

00:08:29.520 --> 00:08:31.440
 So and it's interesting.

00:08:31.440 --> 00:08:36.680
 These hormones, they seem very complicated so that when we, as you pointed out before,

00:08:36.680 --> 00:08:42.120
 try to name them by one purpose that they might have, it gets very confusing.

00:08:42.120 --> 00:08:47.840
 So we think of progesterone as, I have been lately thinking of it as the female fertility

00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:52.720
 hormone, but there you have it, that men are actually producing it in their testicles or

00:08:52.720 --> 00:08:53.720
 pituitary.

00:08:53.720 --> 00:08:59.920
 And then negative effects that they were experiencing from their vasectomies were actually potent,

00:08:59.920 --> 00:09:01.840
 wasn't it, one of the negative effects?

00:09:01.840 --> 00:09:02.840
 Yeah.

00:09:02.840 --> 00:09:08.720
 And I've seen several men, I don't remember whether they had vasectomies or not, but they

00:09:08.720 --> 00:09:16.680
 were suffering from impotency and it just immediately was resolved by taking just very

00:09:16.680 --> 00:09:20.960
 small doses a couple of times of progesterone.

00:09:20.960 --> 00:09:23.680
 It's sort of like priming the pump.

00:09:23.680 --> 00:09:30.800
 Progesterone has a positive feedback apparently in men as well as in women.

00:09:30.800 --> 00:09:39.000
 People have experimented with slices of either ovary tissue or adrenal tissue which makes

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:41.160
 some progesterone.

00:09:41.160 --> 00:09:50.080
 And they found in both cases that if you add a little bit of progesterone, it increases

00:09:50.080 --> 00:10:01.320
 the organ's production of progesterone, positive feedback, which is unusual in hormone regulation.

00:10:01.320 --> 00:10:06.280
 And that indicates to me that the body doesn't see it as something you can get too much of.

00:10:06.280 --> 00:10:07.680
 Yeah.

00:10:07.680 --> 00:10:13.560
 From that kind of engineering, you would think that the body believes that more is always

00:10:13.560 --> 00:10:18.360
 better in the case of progesterone.

00:10:18.360 --> 00:10:24.680
 Which seems to be what happens in pregnancy.

00:10:24.680 --> 00:10:30.120
 If a person is having some biological problem where their progesterone drops off and they

00:10:30.120 --> 00:10:38.480
 start bleeding during the pregnancy, there have been studies where women who habitually

00:10:38.480 --> 00:10:44.080
 either miscarried or had monthly bleeding every month of the pregnancy and then delivered

00:10:44.080 --> 00:10:51.480
 at five or six months, maybe seven months, they would give early in the pregnancy one

00:10:51.480 --> 00:11:00.680
 shot of progesterone and I think it was two-thirds of the women maintained full increasing production

00:11:00.680 --> 00:11:07.920
 every week higher than the preceding week until they had a normal nine-month delivery.

00:11:07.920 --> 00:11:17.120
 Another, I think it was about 30%, required a second injection several weeks later after

00:11:17.120 --> 00:11:25.200
 the first one and they too went back to the full production.

00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:34.720
 I forget the percentages exactly, there was a small group which didn't recover so completely.

00:11:34.720 --> 00:11:39.720
 And I know a lot of people are going in for fertility therapy in this day and age, I don't

00:11:39.720 --> 00:11:45.600
 know if it's more than in the past, but do you know, does progesterone still play a big

00:11:45.600 --> 00:11:48.720
 role in modern fertility therapies?

00:11:48.720 --> 00:11:59.840
 Yeah, but very few of the clinics that specialize in that really understand, if they would read

00:11:59.840 --> 00:12:08.600
 more animal research, they would understand people better, but there's really a medical

00:12:08.600 --> 00:12:16.440
 bias against endocrine science based on animals.

00:12:16.440 --> 00:12:19.280
 And why is that, do you think?

00:12:19.280 --> 00:12:23.600
 I think the marketing thing has done it.

00:12:23.600 --> 00:12:30.600
 After 40 or 50 years, the estrogen industry said don't pay any attention to the fact that

00:12:30.600 --> 00:12:40.000
 estrogen causes clotting, heart attacks, cancer, brain damage, and so on.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:45.720
 That's just in animals, but it has just the opposite effects in humans.

00:12:45.720 --> 00:12:49.880
 That's interesting, yeah, it does seem that they've thrown out a lot of the earlier research

00:12:49.880 --> 00:12:55.800
 that was done back, that you write about quite a bit, back in the early 20th century.

00:12:55.800 --> 00:13:04.600
 And when the industry wants to sell something that they can't demonstrate in humans, then

00:13:04.600 --> 00:13:12.120
 they will base the whole thing on animal experiments, like the osteoporosis thing.

00:13:12.120 --> 00:13:18.800
 They found that there was no evidence that they could demonstrate bone improvement with

00:13:18.800 --> 00:13:20.600
 estrogen in people.

00:13:20.600 --> 00:13:26.280
 So they looked around at different animals, tried it on beagle dogs, found that it caused

00:13:26.280 --> 00:13:32.560
 more osteoporosis in dogs, and so they forgot about that and looked around, found that in

00:13:32.560 --> 00:13:41.800
 rodents it could seem to be causing increased bone strength.

00:13:41.800 --> 00:13:49.560
 But it happens that in rodents, even cortisol can increase bone strength.

00:13:49.560 --> 00:13:56.320
 There are some situations like prolactin in rats will increase progesterone, where in

00:13:56.320 --> 00:14:02.400
 humans it generally decreases it.

00:14:02.400 --> 00:14:08.400
 If you look at the interactions, it's really all the same principles that apply in people.

00:14:08.400 --> 00:14:14.160
 But for example, rodents are generally nocturnal animals and we aren't.

00:14:14.160 --> 00:14:22.120
 And so you have to take into account what time of day you give the injections, because

00:14:22.120 --> 00:14:31.200
 you're either intensifying or weakening their normal rhythms.

00:14:31.200 --> 00:14:38.760
 And by using animals with an upside-down rhythm compared to humans, you can sometimes get

00:14:38.760 --> 00:14:40.600
 very nice upside-down results.

00:14:40.600 --> 00:14:41.600
 I see.

00:14:41.600 --> 00:14:45.160
 And you're saying that the pharmaceutical companies who are paying for these studies

00:14:45.160 --> 00:14:48.720
 are actually engineering them that way on purpose.

00:14:48.720 --> 00:14:49.720
 Yeah.

00:14:49.720 --> 00:14:56.480
 They like rat experiments when they can be arranged to sell a product, but they want

00:14:56.480 --> 00:15:06.680
 to forget completely about the dog experiments which cause only bad effects.

00:15:06.680 --> 00:15:12.880
 Going back to estrogen and progesterone, which is the subject of our show today, effect on

00:15:12.880 --> 00:15:19.440
 fertility or contraception, I was curious if there's any effect on estrogen or progesterone

00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:25.480
 production when somebody gets a tubal ligation.

00:15:25.480 --> 00:15:32.840
 Because at the same time that the impotency experiment saw that in men, some other group

00:15:32.840 --> 00:15:40.800
 within just a month or two of that publication saw exactly that effect in the result of the

00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:43.160
 tubal ligation.

00:15:43.160 --> 00:15:51.080
 And that really helped to explain how IUDs work.

00:15:51.080 --> 00:15:59.400
 And animal experiments had been demonstrating that for years, that if you want to have the

00:15:59.400 --> 00:16:05.360
 animal become infertile, you just put a little suture in the uterus.

00:16:05.360 --> 00:16:07.060
 That's usually all it takes.

00:16:07.060 --> 00:16:14.400
 And the signal travels up from the slightly injured uterus to turn off the ovary progesterone

00:16:14.400 --> 00:16:15.400
 production.

00:16:15.400 --> 00:16:23.240
 And so injuring the tubes does the same thing.

00:16:23.240 --> 00:16:25.720
 Not always, but often.

00:16:25.720 --> 00:16:31.400
 So that could lead to a progesterone deficiency in somebody who's either had an IUD or a tubal

00:16:31.400 --> 00:16:32.400
 ligation.

00:16:32.400 --> 00:16:33.400
 Yeah.

00:16:33.400 --> 00:16:34.400
 Yeah.

00:16:34.400 --> 00:16:35.400
 Huh.

00:16:35.400 --> 00:16:41.960
 So let's, if you don't mind, we'll pick up where we left off in your sort of life's path.

